The interior of this restaurant was light and airy on a Sunday afternoon, contrasting with a gritty homeless scene outside. We were seated immediately, and generally service was attentive. There was a small jazz combo playing pleasant music, which however rendered conversation difficult. Our table had a wobbly leg, and as soon as I sat down my foot displaced it in such a way that the water glasses sloshed their contents onto the tablecloth. Nice being the clod at dinner, isn't it? For me, the most appetizing dish at our table was the shrimp in grits/cornmeal, which looked like a cheese and shrimp casserole. It had a small bite, but the spice did not overwhelm the shrimp. I wanted to try the gumbo, but I'm not a big fan of okra or spicy-hot dishes. (You might wonder what I was doing there at all, but one does what one's friends want, right?) As an economical and presumably safe measure, I ordered the beignets. The heavy starch overwhelmed most of the other flavors, and finishing the four was unexpectedly difficult. In my distant memory of stopping at Café du Monde on misty New Orleans mornings, beignets were more delicate and airy. The croque monsieur looked plentiful. I didn't sample it, but the appearance was that of french toast made with thick bread. Rather than taking my word, you're going to have to try this one for yourself. Unlike some of the reviewers here, we didn't have any trouble getting in, so perhaps Sunday afternoon is not a bad choice.

Brenda's is the place to eat if you want a food trip experience to New Orleans. I came to Brenda's on Saturday for lunch but they serve brunch until 3pm on Saturdays. I love the classic beignet & crawfish beignet. I came here with a friend and they ate the pork belly grits omg a bite of that has so much savory flavor it's to die for. I had the catfish egg Benedict the catfish cornmeal breading is so fresh and delicious. The buttermilk biscuit with catfish egg Benedict melt in your mouth. The catfish dish is so delicious. I'm definitely coming back for lunch or dinner to try their po boys and gumbo.

Brunch today was heaven. Little bit of a wait, well worth it. The waitstaff greeted us right away and was super cheerful. Everything we ordered was AMAZING. The iced coffee. omg. The spicy chicken sandwich? Cooked and assembled perfectly. Let us choose between fries, slaw or half & half. You mean I don't have to choose?! Amazing. Such a great experience. Once of the best places I've eaten in SF.

Some of the best Cajun food I've had outside of New Orleans! This was my first stop in San Fransisco, and while I did have the thought that I should go somewhere serving more regional cuisine, I couldn't resist the menu. So glad I came in! We started with their bloody Mary, which comes with pickled okra. We split an order of three Crawfish Beignets. Please be aware, if you are also ordering entrees you really don't need three of these split between two people. They are massive and filling and jesus christ some of the best things you'll ever eat. They are savory, and super moist on the inside with scallions, cayenne, and cheddar. When you open it up it's almost saucy, bursting with flavor, tender crawfish. Ooompf! The gumbo is also a real winner! It's got chicken, okra, and sausage! All the good things! My boy ordered the Cajun omelet, and the pictures really don't do it justice. It did some with an overabundance of cheddar, quite a bit of which we ended up scraping off. It had crawfish and sausage and pretty much everything else in it, this was a special so I don't know how often it's on the menu but you'd be a fool not to order it when you see it. Comes with home fries and a biscuit. I ordered the eggs Benedict with fried green tomatoes and bacon, and then I also got it with a side of pulled pork because I'm ridiculous. I wasn't in love with the tomatoes, but the pork was on point! On the tables along with some other condiments they also have these jars of apple jam that are really more like apple pie filling: sweet and gooey and delicious, they go great on the beignets! Service was a little brusque but never unfriendly. This was such a delicious meal, I wish we had this place in NYC.

If you don't mind waiting an hour plus for brunch on a Sunday then you're already prepared. Located in a slightly interesting area the restaurant has an attached coffee shop you can order from while you wait (wonderfully priced, so kudos on that). Understand, getting seated goes by party size not what time you put yourself on the list. Nothing (including the shrimp and grits) is spicy. Food was decent but to purchase one pancake it was $5 or $6.50 for a special pancake, so I was a tad grouchy. The mimosa was good (look toward the blackboard with specials of the day) but my side order of andouille sausage was mildly warm and the shrimp and gravy for my 'shrimp and grits' dish was also mildly warm. Waiter took our orders down, delivered food and brought the check (they do not provide separate billing but will split it amongst credit cards and cash). Nothing over the top in terms of service. It's a good restaurant but between prices, Luke warm food, and the extensive wait, was not a fan for what's considered a top food experience and what's deemed as soulful french cuisine (no where close!!)

Brenda's is the epitome of a comfort food establishment. A cozy and small hole in the wall and the only indication it's there is the mass of people congregating outside...with reason. Their food is simply delicious. They take southern, French soul food and add an elegant twist to it. Their cream biscuits are hands down the best I've ever had. Their portions are huge and their prices are very affordable! Their crawfish beignets are so so good! My only critique is that, as a pretty big company, I don't understand why they can't split checks especially for huge parties. The wait time is pretty long as well but like I said, the food is delicious. Just a tip: they won't seat you unless your whole party is there. Which I also don't like seeing as though the wait is long and the restaurant is tiny. Definitely come check this place out!

My family took me here for my 31st birthday, and as the self-appointed restaurant chooser of the group, I was a bit skeptical (not that I know the SF food scene), but I decided NOT to read Yelp reviews before I went so I wouldn't get in my own head. We had a GREAT brunch meal filled with southern deliciousness - here's a tour! Top Dog: Grits - pretty much everyone had grits, with shrimp, with pork belly, as a side to a seafood frittata - the full grits helping was topped with a tomato-based sauce and delicious meats, all on a bed of creamy, buttery, cheesy grits. Shout out to the delicious pork belly with my grits, as well to the poppin' shrimp. Contender: French Toast - never really though of french toast as from France (think fries), but this perfectly cooked, nut-topped variety was plain, but elegant and delicious, great balance of butter and sugar profiles. Surprising: sweet beignets - I've always felt like I have to like beignets, but they're just the plainest donut - no glaze, no topping, no filling - just too much powdered sugar that you accidentally inhale and it makes you cough. These beignets, were delicious, but also upped the ante with chocolate and apple filling Disappointing: crawfish beignet - at first I thought that it was just a savory cajun spice dusting on the top of the beignet - NOPE, there's bits of meat in there, and while it was good, it just didn't hold it's own along with the sweet beignets. I don't know when I would want 'french donut' as the delivery system for 'cajun seafood' flavors - it was like a gumbo-filed donut - when would I be in the mood for that? Again, flavors on point, but not my fave. Along with big mugs of coffee, a great birthday breakfast - thanks, Brenda!

Reviews/pics of food looked great, so With rumors of long lines and no reservation option, the friends and I decided to get there super early on Saturday for brunch. There were only a few other people waiting so we were able to get in right when the restaurant opened. Charming décor, cozy setup of the tables - definite French twist. Service was good. Our group started off with the beignet flight - but everyone opted for the Crawfish beignet. I was pleasantly surprised that FINALLY, after trying several places where I live that advertise "Crawfish beignets" that are actually more like hushpuppies, Brenda's actually does it like a true New Orleans type fluffy pastry, filled in the center with delicious crawfish and dusted with cayenne pepper. The crawfish was deliciously spiced - thought there was a little too much of the beignet itself (too thick?) - but I scooped out and finished the delicious crawfish filling! Most of my group ordered the Shrimp & Grits, which they all cleaned their plates so I would say it was a hit. I got the Creole Veggie Omelette which boasted a corn maque choux as one of the fillings. It was a very generous portion plate - omelette, big biscuit, and sweet potato hash. I thought the maque choux would have a little more creole flavor than it did, and was not too crazy about the sweet potato hash flavors either. They were ok. The biscuit was tasty with the jelly provided. To drink, I had a mimosa. The waiter did inform us that the Champagne to juice ratio was in favor of more Champagne with a touch of juice, however I didn't like the taste of the orange juice so it threw off the whole mimosa. Another friend got a different juice and voiced a similar opinion. Would have probably done better to just get the Champagne on its own. Overall, the restaurant is cute, but I didn't get a true "soul food" feel from the meal I ordered.

Had the oyster flight, which was excellent, and the fried chicken dinner, which was also quite good. Service was prompt and friendly. I went a little early to beat the rush since they don't take reservations; there was definitely a line out the door when I left.

    7/8/2018

    The interior of this restaurant was light and airy on a Sunday afternoon, contrasting with a gritty homeless scene outside. We were seated immediately, and generally service was attentive. There was a small jazz combo playing pleasant music, which however rendered conversation difficult.

    Our table had a wobbly leg, and as soon as I sat down my foot displaced it in such a way that the water glasses sloshed their contents onto the tablecloth. Nice being the clod at dinner, isn't it?

    For me, the most appetizing dish at our table was the shrimp in grits/cornmeal, which looked like a cheese and shrimp casserole. It had a small bite, but the spice did not overwhelm the shrimp.

    I wanted to try the gumbo, but I'm not a big fan of okra or spicy-hot dishes. (You might wonder what I was doing there at all, but one does what one's friends want, right?)

    As an economical and presumably safe measure, I ordered the beignets. The heavy starch overwhelmed most of the other flavors, and finishing the four was unexpectedly difficult. In my distant memory of stopping at Café du Monde on misty New Orleans mornings, beignets were more delicate and airy.

    The croque monsieur looked plentiful. I didn't sample it, but the appearance was that of french toast made with thick bread.

    Rather than taking my word, you're going to have to try this one for yourself. Unlike some of the reviewers here, we didn't have any trouble getting in, so perhaps Sunday afternoon is not a bad choice.

    Some of the best Cajun food I've had outside of New Orleans!

    This was my first stop in San Fransisco, and while I did have the thought that I should go somewhere serving more regional cuisine, I couldn't resist the menu. So glad I came in!

    We started with their bloody Mary, which comes with pickled okra.

    We split an order of three Crawfish Beignets. Please be aware, if you are also ordering entrees you really don't need three of these split between two people. They are massive and filling and jesus christ some of the best things you'll ever eat. They are savory, and super moist on the inside with scallions, cayenne, and cheddar. When you open it up it's almost saucy, bursting with flavor, tender crawfish. Ooompf!

    The gumbo is also a real winner! It's got chicken, okra, and sausage! All the good things!

    My boy ordered the Cajun omelet, and the pictures really don't do it justice. It did some with an overabundance of cheddar, quite a bit of which we ended up scraping off. It had crawfish and sausage and pretty much everything else in it, this was a special so I don't know how often it's on the menu but you'd be a fool not to order it when you see it. Comes with home fries and a biscuit.

    I ordered the eggs Benedict with fried green tomatoes and bacon, and then I also got it with a side of pulled pork because I'm ridiculous. I wasn't in love with the tomatoes, but the pork was on point!

    On the tables along with some other condiments they also have these jars of apple jam that are really more like apple pie filling: sweet and gooey and delicious, they go great on the beignets!

    Service was a little brusque but never unfriendly. This was such a delicious meal, I wish we had this place in NYC.

Shout out to the delicious pork belly with my grits, as well to the poppin' shrimp.

    Contender: French Toast - never really though of french toast as from France (think fries), but this perfectly cooked, nut-topped variety was plain, but elegant and delicious, great balance of butter and sugar profiles.

    Surprising:  sweet beignets - I've always felt like I have to like beignets, but they're just the plainest donut - no glaze, no topping, no filling - just too much powdered sugar that you accidentally inhale and it makes you cough.  These beignets, were delicious, but also upped the ante with chocolate and apple filling

    Disappointing: crawfish beignet - at first I thought that it was just a savory cajun spice dusting on the top of the beignet - NOPE, there's bits of meat in there, and while it was good, it just didn't hold it's own along with the sweet beignets.  I don't know when I would want 'french donut' as the delivery system for 'cajun seafood' flavors - it was like a gumbo-filed donut - when would I be in the mood for that?  Again, flavors on point, but not my fave.

    Along with big mugs of coffee, a great birthday breakfast - thanks, Brenda!

    Came for brunch on a Sunday and there already a long list of people waiting around 10am. Make sure when you get there, write your name down on the chalkboard and stick around the front to wait for them to call your name for roll call and to be seated. We stood near the door by the exit and could barely hear our name.

    Upon seated, I already know what to order because I've done my research.

    Watermelon Tea (4/5)
    Tea was very refreshing and not too sweet. Free refills!

    Crawfish beignet (2/5)
    TBH, this was just okay to me. I felt like the dough was a little too much and not enough filling. I used some of my shrimp and grits to make it more flavorful. Each order comes with 3 big beignets.

    Shrimp & Grits (5/5)
    LOVE LOVE this dish. It was very delicious and the the flavors were out of this world. I would lick this plate clean if the server didn't stack our plates on top of our grits when we were still working on it.

    Fried Chicken Benedict (3/5)
    Not of fan of their biscuit but their take on their sauce for the Benedict was good.

    Creole Seafood Fritata (2/5)
    Didn't really see the seafood was that mentioned to be in the fritata, kind of just taste like a regular egg dish.

    They also shorted me my change. Maybe I should have counted my change correctly but I didn't realize it until we have reached the outskirts of Downtown SF. I paid $100 on a $67.71 bill and got $22.29 change and I tipped like $10. Enjoy my generous 30% tip. They also include a surcharge of 2% for the SF health ordinance.

    Reviews/pics of food looked great, so With rumors of long lines and no reservation option, the friends and I decided to get there super early on Saturday for brunch. There were only a few other people waiting so we were able to get in right when the restaurant opened. Charming décor, cozy setup of the tables - definite French twist. Service was good.

    Our group started off with the beignet flight - but everyone opted for the Crawfish beignet. I was pleasantly surprised that FINALLY, after trying several places where I live that advertise "Crawfish beignets" that are actually more like hushpuppies, Brenda's actually does it like a true New Orleans type fluffy pastry, filled in the center with delicious crawfish and dusted with cayenne pepper. The crawfish was deliciously spiced - thought there was a little too much of the beignet itself (too thick?) - but I scooped out and finished the delicious crawfish filling!

    Most of my group ordered the Shrimp & Grits, which they all cleaned their plates so I would say it was a hit. I got the Creole Veggie Omelette which boasted a corn maque choux as one of the fillings. It was a very generous portion plate - omelette, big biscuit, and sweet potato hash. I thought the maque choux would have a little more creole flavor than it did, and was not too crazy about the sweet potato hash flavors either. They were ok. The biscuit was tasty with the jelly provided. To drink, I had a mimosa. The waiter did inform us that the Champagne to juice ratio was in favor of more Champagne with a touch of juice, however I didn't like the taste of the orange juice so it threw off the whole mimosa. Another friend got a different juice and voiced a similar opinion. Would have probably done better to just get the Champagne on its own. Overall, the restaurant is cute, but I didn't get a true "soul food" feel from the meal I ordered.
